Text: One thing that we as a group have definitely improved this week was communication.
Basically, we talked to each other more regularly, be it online or offline.
We also let each other know our concerns and where our interests lie in the current project.
Every now and then, we would just drop a link or picture to share what we accomplished into our Facebook group chat.
Everyone knew when other members were making good progress, and what concerns or roadblocks they might be having.
We also proactively set up a dedicated Slack channel with Eric, and thanks to his input we all start to have a better picture of what is it that we're building.
Just an hour ago, Eric requested satellite imagery and I did some research into certain legal issues surrounding using Google Map to give Kuku and Bibi some head-up.
Noticing that we haven't set down a fixed weekly meeting, Koko did just that and proposed that we set aside some time on Tuesday.
Throughout the week, I also reached out to each member individually to work out shared tasks and organized group-study session if possible.
This stream of collaboration has greatly increased our team's productivity and a sense of teamwork.

Communication becomes smoother and less of a burden when everyone chips in, and I've learnt that even when my teammates seem reserved, perhaps they're just waiting for someone to start the conversation.
Even better, or maybe not since it's already half-way into our project, our roles have changed after we finally had some thoughtful discussions about our roles.
In particular, it turned out that Kuku enjoyed coding the front-end logic more than the back-end.
The fact that Bibi has gone ahead and taken care of the login also showed that he may not like the server-side that much.
Looking back, we definitely rushed through the process and simply assign what is convenient rather than what is suitable.
Had we taken the time to hear each other out a bit better, we could've reached the current stage sooner.
Speaking of the current situation, I've assumed full responsibility for the back-end, and Bibi and Kuku have paired up as our front-end devs.
Poor old Koko is still stuck with Pandas and tables, I'm afraid, but at least we've worked out as a group the final schema of our database and can start gluing things together.
The fact that this is delayed by more than a week makes me think that there are cases where a user-story should be handled by everyone involved.
Our schema is not even finalized as we're still waiting for Eric's feedback, but that only emphasizes how important these tasks are to the whole development process.
We did not think it through when we just agreed that Bibi would make an ERD and then that would be it.
Even when we knew that Bibi was sick last weekend, none of us actually thought about picking up this design issue.
Role assignment shouldn't be rigid and people shouldn't feel pigeon-holed into doing things simply because they've done it before or simply because that's the only task left.
As teammate I think we should all help each other to articulate and strive toward what they really want to learn and to do.
On a more practical note, I've managed to set up and deploy an API using Node and Express.
Since this post's too long already, I won't go into the technical reasons for choosing MongoDB over MySQL, but that will definitely be a major part in my final report.
In short, it turned out that MongoDB supports geospatial queries and gives us much more flexibility in handling varied data sets.

While the API is live and connected to a cloud database (https: //us-mines-api.herokuapp.com/mines/), the next step would be to research about API design best practices to implement some routes for our client-side (something like /mines/@latitude-longitude/etc.).
Specifically, I'll be looking at how big companies design their mapping routes such as Google or Bing and go from there.
Another approach is to do some real geo-searches and look at their URL and the browser's network tab.
I will also ask for Bibi, Kuku and Eric's input as they will be the ones who consume my API.
Finally, I will also try to pick up some basic regex to help with parsing parameters from the client.
Another thing that I would like to start on is to start writing tests for the API once 2 or 3 basic routes have been set up.
The overall goal is to have an API that serves the map as well as the app that Kuku's has already built for Eric.
This I think would simplify things for Kuku as he just needs to learn the routes and incorporate new data into his application.
Besides, we can always add more routes to serve much more specific needs along the way.

Eric has told us that if we did a good job he may hire us to maintain the whole thing, so I personally feel this change of design is a good investment as it gets me to think in long terms rather than just visualizing coordinates on a map.
Lastly, I would of course definitely try to keep and improve the streak of good communication among our team.
Overall
